body":"The home a celebrated architect built for her family held White House china from her grandfather's table, some of it now in the Smithsonian. She kept the Roosevelt past close at hand.","number":3}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Edith Roosevelt","last_name":"Williams","display_name":"Edith Roosevelt Derby Williams","gender":"female","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"TR's granddaughter; historian and conservationist"},"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Republican Committeewoman","organization":"Washington State"},{"role":"Founder","organization":"Vashon Island Health Center"},{"role":"Trustee","organization":"University of Washington","start_year":1975,"end_year":1981}],"birth":{"year":1917,"country":"United States","month":6,"day":17},"death":{"year":2008,"country":"United States","month":6,"day":8,"city":"Vashon","state":"Washington"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM780"},"education":[],"slug":"edith-roosevelt-williams-1917"},"I1667":{"id":"I1667","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"X3158","mother_id":"X3159"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6088","children_ids":["HD6119","HD6120","HD6121","HD6122"],"marriage_number":1,"marriage_year":1913}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"military","header":"Division surgeon under fire in France","body":"He served fourteen months as surgeon of the Second Infantry Division, wounded in the field and decorated by France with the Croix de Guerre and the Legion of Honor. The American army added its Distinguished Service Medal.","number":1},{"category":"career","header":"He rebuilt hospital care across Long Island","body":"For some thirty years after the war he led surgery at the Glen Cove hospital and drove the founding of a new laboratory there, later named in his honor. Friends raised a quarter of a million dollars to build it.","number":2},{"category":"character","header":"A hunter in his father-in-law's mold","body":"Like Theodore Roosevelt he loved big game, stalking Kodiak bear in Alaska and filming moose on long northern trips. He titled his own war memoir Wade in, Sanitary.","number":3}],"sources":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Richard","last_name":"Derby","display_name":"Dr. Richard Derby","gender":"male","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Surgeon; TR's son-in-law and WWI division surgeon","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781015142/derby_mv5lmq.png"},"military_service":[{"war":"World War I","branch":"United States Army","rank":"Lieutenant Colonel","unit":"2nd Infantry Division","notes":"Division surgeon in France; Croix de Guerre, Legion of Honor, Distinguished Service Medal."}],"career":[{"role":"Surgeon","organization":"Roosevelt and St. Luke's Hospitals","start_year":1910,"end_year":1917},{"role":"Chief of Surgery","organization":"Community Hospital, Glen Cove"},{"role":"Member","organization":"Nassau County Board of Health","start_year":1938}],"birth":{"year":1881,"country":"United States","month":4,"day":7},"death":{"year":1963,"country":"United States","month":7,"day":21,"city":"Brattleboro","state":"Vermont"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM768"},"education":[{"institution_id":"INST002","dates":"1903","type":"graduation","notes":"A.B."},{"school_name":"Columbia P&S","dates":"1907","type":"graduation","notes":"M.D."}],"slug":"richard-derby-1881"},"HD6088":{"id":"HD6088","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"generation_from_thomas":10},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"X00744","mother_id":"HD6083"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I1667","children_ids":["HD6119","HD6120","HD6121","HD6122"],"marriage_number":1,"marriage_year":1913}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"social_reform","header":"She nursed the wounded in wartime France","body":"Early in the First World War she went to Paris with her husband and worked at the American Ambulance Hospital while he operated on men brought in from the front. She came home to decades of civic and hospital work on Long Island.","number":1},{"category":"legacy","header":"She made Sagamore Hill a national shrine","body":"More than anyone she pushed to preserve her father's home, Sagamore Hill, as a public historic site, and guarded the Roosevelt papers given to Harvard. In Oyster Bay, where she fought for low-income housing, neighbors called her the Queen of Oyster Bay.","number":2},{"category":"legacy","header":"One of the museum's first women trustees","body":"She became one of the first two women on the board of the American Museum of Natural History, the institution her grandfather had helped found. She also chaired the Nassau County Nursing Service and led the county's Red Cross.","number":3},{"category":"character","header":"Painted in her Red Cross uniform","body":"For her formal family portrait she chose to sit in her Red Cross uniform rather than evening dress and jewels. She gave the organization some sixty years and chaired its Nassau County work.","number":4},{"category":"character","header":"The Roosevelt child who stayed close to home","body":"Of all the president's children she was the steady one, anchoring the family at Oyster Bay long after her brothers scattered to wars and far places. She married the surgeon who would tend the wounded beside her in France.","number":5}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X3158","display_label":"was her father-in-law, a New York eye-surgery pioneer"},{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X3159","display_label":"was her mother-in-law, painted by John Singer Sargent"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Ethel Carow","last_name":"Roosevelt","display_name":"Ethel Carow Roosevelt Derby","gender":"female","bio_blurb":"TR's only surviving daughter by Edith Carow","maiden_name":"Roosevelt","married_names":["Derby"],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781015031/5997_126463715689_yo7bbl.jpg"},"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Volunteer nurse","organization":"American Ambulance Hospital, Paris","start_year":1915},{"role":"County Chairman","organization":"American Red Cross"},{"role":"Chairman","organization":"Nassau County Nursing Service"},{"role":"Trustee","organization":"American Museum of Natural History"},{"role":"Trustee","organization":"Theodore Roosevelt Association"}],"birth":{"year":1891,"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1977,"country":"United States","city":"Oyster Bay","state":"New York"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM768"},"education":[{"school_name":"National Cathedral School","dates":"1906"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"slug":"ethel-carow-roosevelt-1891"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}